s have always implicitly or explicitly addressed issues of gender and highlighted the significance of present and future families to American society. This is the insight underpinning Isabel Heinemann’s groundbreaking study, which traces, over the course of the twentieth century, debates on the family and its role; the relationship between the individual and society; and individual decision-making rights as well as their denial or curtailment. Unpacking these issues in a vivid and innovative analysis, the book recounts the prehistory of current conflicts over the family and gender while illuminating the relationship between social change, normative shifts, and the counter-movements spawned in response to them.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFamilieszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxEmploymentzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aEhe. 4aFrauenarbeit. 4aGesellschaftlicher Wandel. 4aVereinigte Staaten von Amerika.  a20th century.  aUnited States of America.  afamily.  amarriage.  asocietal change.  aworking women.1 aSkinner, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG0 cEPUBz97831110361680 cprintz978311103553640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311103612040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111036120423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111036120/origina